<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Hacking_in_Shadowrun_Unlimited">Hacking in Shadowrun Unlimited</span></h2>
<p>This is a system that looks simple but has an underlying complexity that keeps things interesting.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Programs">Programs</span></h3>
<p>For Shadowrun Unlimited, there are three kinds of programs a decker uses:
</p>
<ul>
<li> Programs that are used on yourself or against ICE. They're stored in your "Stash" and loaded into your deck each time you jack into the Matrix.
</li>
<li> Programs listed under "Mission Items" that allow you to overcome the built-in security in a computer network (SAN, SPU, CPU) and edit, delete, download, or browse files to complete the requirements of the job. You don't have to interact with these programs other than to purchase them, they stay loaded at all times.
</li>
<li> ESPs, which allow you to summon offensive or defensive AIs in the Matrix. They're like a summoned creature or pet.
</li>
</ul>
<p>ICE is like a monster or enemy in the Matrix. If you've failed at cracking some of the security then ICE will be summoned and you either have to defeat it in battle or get kicked out of the system. Some areas in a Matrix run may have a barrier guarded by ICE.
</p><p>The programs can be a little confusing. The simplified explanation: The Mission Item programs allow you to overcome internal security to _avoid_ dealing with ICE. If you fail, ICE is summoned and then you use your Stash programs to battle the ICE. ESPs also help you to deal with ICE.
</p><p>A decker who prefers to avoid Matrix combat will have better Mission Item programs than Stash programs. A decker who likes lots of combat will have the best Stash programs and weaker Mission Item programs. All deckers should have both (with an ESP or two "just in case").
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Making_Money_As_A_Decker">Making Money As A Decker</span></h3>
<p>A note about payments: The "real" payout in a decking job isn't the fee from the fixer, it's the profits from selling data. Emails, client listings, project plans. There's a wealth of information hiding in these systems and fences are happy to pay you well for them. The best individual data items can pay as much as the fixer fee, and you can haul out as many as six data items at once! A run with a fixer fee of 1200Y can end up being worth around 8000Y after you visit your data fence. When you get a new deck, make sure to increase the storage as soon as you can afford, to better haul out your electronic "loot".
</p><p>Your first decking job will probably be for Eric, hacking into the Organ Grinder's computer. You might want to pick up a couple cheap Stash programs from <a href="/wiki/index.php/Quick_Jack" title="Quick Jack">Quick Jack</a> as you may trigger ICE with weak skills. I like Degrade I, Killer I, and Medic I. Others may prefer to swap out Degrade for an AOE, or use Shield I instead of Medic I. Eric will offer this job multiple times if you keep running for him.
</p><p>Once you can ghost through Organ Grinder's reliably, give the "Hack a random system" option a try on any Matrix link. It only works if you don't have a fixer job in the queue. The target numbers should be 4-6 in the random runs, which should be do-able with just a modest investment in Mission Item programs. You should plan for Masking 2, Exploit 2, and Spoof 2. If you're unlucky you'll only get to "old" files (worth about 100-200Y each). With a few lucky rolls, you can reach the mid-tier files worth 500Y each. As you can afford it, upgrade your cyberdeck storage and pick up a couple level 2 Stash programs. For now the CPU area is too hard to crack with low decking skills and only a few programs, but I'm hoping that will change in the future.
</p><p>That starter Sony can't hold powerful programs. With a Decking skill of 4 and all my Mission Item programs at 2, I can complete some random Hacking runs. Each one is worth cash. Deckers have a lot of programs to buy, it's why the missions pay so well. Just be slow and patient. After every run or two drop by the Hub and check prices.
</p><p>Eventually you'll be ghosting through these runs without triggering any ICE at all. At that point, you should have enough in your credstick to buy a nice weapon or a cheap cybernetic enhancement.
</p><p>Avoid runs from Eric that require a lot of killing, I like the Drug Dealer mission (you can usually kill him with a machete), the Elf package, the Suit (escorting Mr. Johnson), and Organ Grinder's decking run (when it's not buggy). Escorting the Decker (Null Zero) is Eric's best paying mission, but risks both a big gang confrontation and a Lone Star police run-in.
</p><p>Once hacking random systems is "easy", it's time to move on to Frosty's decker missions. You should be able to do Frosty's missions with your starter Sony cyberdeck, as long as you have a decent setup (Maxed out Mission Item programs and a few sturdy Stash programs), and a Decking skill of 5. Each mission will have multiple tests, starting with a target number of 4 or 5, and moving up to the challenging CPU area with a target of 9. Once you can reliably crack that tough CPU nut, your cash flow will be steady as you haul in up to six data files worth over 1100-1200Y each. Frosty can sell you your next two decks, and whatever Stash programs you're missing or want to improve.
</p><p>As you improve, you can buy better cyberdecks and programs, as well as moving to a nicer Safe House and keeping a Doc Wagon contract available.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Decker_Skills">Decker Skills</span></h3>
<p>For now, the "holy grail" of cyberdecks needs a Decking of 7. But deckers start with much lower skills and a basic Sony deck.
</p><p>With that basic Sony deck, you probably 'need' a 5 in Decking and 2's in all your Mission Item programs (the best it can hold) to get through Frosty's data runs with any regularity. Even so, you'll want good Stash programs as you'll trigger ICE (on average) at least once a run.
</p><p>If you can save your pennies and buy the second deck (around 22,500Y), that all changes. You'll have more AP, you can use higher level Mission Item programs (which are dirt cheap compared to the deck costs) and Frosty's decking missions become mind-numbingly easy even with no further increase in Decking skills. At this point you can just ghost through the missions and collect both cash (from fenced data) and Karma. Pick up the third cyberdeck, a Fuchi, and max out the storage, and you'll be swimming in nuyen.
</p><p>That would hint that success in Shadowrun Unlimited decking is gated behind access to higher levels of Mission Item programs. I don't see a real need to increase Decking past 5 unless you want the bragging rights that comes with the uber-cyberdeck.
</p><p>Once you have that 5 in Decking, I'd focus on getting as much Body as you can handle (more Hit Points are NEVER a bad thing), and filling in your Non-Combat skills or whatever damage source you prefer. Do you want a rigging drone, a melee weapon, do you like guns?
</p><p>Save the 7 Decking for when you're at a lull in the storyline mission and don't mind the grind.
</p>
